docs.abstract: President Trump’s head-spinning moves on national security, the budget and trade left Washington reeling and a bewildered sense of resignation in the West Wing.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s head-spinning moves on national security, the budget and trade left Washington reeling and a bewildered sense of resignation in the West Wing.
docs.lead_paragraph: PALM BEACH, Fla. — President Trump decamped to his oceanfront estate here on Friday after a head-spinning series of presidential decisions on national security, trade and the budget that left the capital reeling and his advisers nervous about what comes next.

headline.main: After Another Week of Chaos, Trump Repairs to Palm Beach. No One Knows What Comes Next.
headline.print_headline: President Unbound, Aides Bewildered, Capital Reeling

byline.original: By Mark Landler and Julie Hirschfeld Davis

docs.abstract: The university is known more for producing the most African-American students who go on to complete combined M.D.-Ph.D. programs than it is for turning out professional athletes.
docs.snippet: The university is known more for producing the most African-American students who go on to complete combined M.D.-Ph.D. programs than it is for turning out professional athletes.
docs.lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — The stunning victory by the University of Maryland, Baltimore County, over the University of Virginia on Friday night — the biggest upset ever in the N.C.A.A. men’s basketball tournament — catapulted a school whose competitive claim to fame had long been chess into sports history.

headline.main: Cinderella Story? It’s True for U.M.B.C. in Academics, Too
headline.print_headline: Underdog School Beats the Odds Again

docs.abstract: After months of internal wrangling, the administration filed a brief urging the justices to turn down an appeal from victims of terrorist attacks in Israel.
docs.snippet: After months of internal wrangling, the administration filed a brief urging the justices to turn down an appeal from victims of terrorist attacks in Israel.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Last June, the Supreme Court asked the Trump administration to file a brief. The justices wanted advice on whether to hear an appeal from victims of terrorist attacks in Israel.

headline.main: The P.L.O. Has an Unlikely Supreme Court Ally: The Trump Administration
headline.print_headline: The P.L.O.’s Unlikely Supreme Court Ally: The Trump Administration

docs.abstract: Senator Thad Cochran of Mississippi, the 10th-longest serving senator in American history, is resigning because of ill health, creating two races in his home state
docs.snippet: Senator Thad Cochran of Mississippi, the 10th-longest serving senator in American history, is resigning because of ill health, creating two races in his home state
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Thad Cochran, an octogenarian Republican from Mississippi who serves as chairman of the powerful Appropriations Committee, announced Monday that he is resigning from the Senate on April 1 because of ill health — a decision that will create two Senate races in his home state in November.

headline.main: Senator Thad Cochran Announces Retirement, Opening Another G.O.P. Seat
headline.print_headline: As Cochran Steps Down, G.O.P. Seat Is Put in Play

byline.original: By Sheryl Gay Stolberg and Jonathan Martin

docs.abstract: Economists question whether tariffs will do much to narrow the trade deficit, and whether policymakers should care about the economic metric at all.
docs.snippet: Economists question whether tariffs will do much to narrow the trade deficit, and whether policymakers should care about the economic metric at all.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s fixation  with America’s widening trade deficit is fueling his decision to impose stiff tariffs on steel and aluminum imports. Only a small group of experts share Mr. Trump’s fixation, and few see tariffs as an effective tool to narrow the so-called trade gap.

headline.main: Trump Hates the Trade Deficit. Most Economists Don’t.
headline.print_headline: Trump Sees Trade Deficit as a Millstone. Most Economists Don’t.

docs.abstract: The delay reflects President Trump’s largely passive response to the interference and doubts by Secretary of State Rex W. Tillerson in his department’s ability to spend its money wisely.
docs.snippet: The delay reflects President Trump’s largely passive response to the interference and doubts by Secretary of State Rex W. Tillerson in his department’s ability to spend its money wisely.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As Russia’s virtual war against the United States continues unabated with the midterm elections approaching, the State Department has yet to spend any of the $120 million it has been allocated since late 2016 to counter foreign efforts to meddle in elections or sow distrust in democracy.

headline.main: State Dept. Was Granted $120 Million to Fight Russian Meddling. It Has Spent $0.
headline.print_headline: State Dept. Holds Funds Aimed to Fight Meddling

docs.abstract: Fearful of hurting their citizenship eligibility or being deported, families are said to be dropping out of the programs even before the administration’s immigration policies are in place.
docs.snippet: Fearful of hurting their citizenship eligibility or being deported, families are said to be dropping out of the programs even before the administration’s immigration policies are in place.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Immigrants hoping for permanent residence are dropping out of public nutrition programs even before prominent elements of the Trump administration’s proposed policy changes are enacted, fearful that participating could threaten their citizenship eligibility or put them at risk for deportation, according to program administrators.

headline.main: Spooked by Trump Proposals, Immigrants Abandon Public Nutrition Services

docs.abstract: Tensions over criminal justice policy have pitted the president’s son-in-law against his attorney general, and resulted in a seesawing approach to prisons.
docs.snippet: Tensions over criminal justice policy have pitted the president’s son-in-law against his attorney general, and resulted in a seesawing approach to prisons.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In the final months of the Obama administration, the Justice Department announced a new approach to preparing prisoners for life beyond their cells. Officials created a prison school system, pledged money for technology training and promised to help prevent former inmates from returning to prison.

headline.main: Sessions and Kushner Square Off, and Prisoners Hang in the Balance
headline.print_headline: Kushner Spars With Sessions, In Whiplash on Prisons Policy

docs.abstract: Thursday was the last day at the White House for the 29-year-old from Connecticut, who followed an unlikely career path to become a presidential confidante.
docs.snippet: Thursday was the last day at the White House for the 29-year-old from Connecticut, who followed an unlikely career path to become a presidential confidante.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Hope Hicks, the White House communications director who worked behind the scenes to direct the president through multiple professional crises — and decided to resign after she found herself exhausted by them — has left the building.

headline.main: Hope Hicks Is Gone, and It’s Not Clear Who Can Replace Her
headline.print_headline: A Longtime Trump Whisperer Packs Up, Leaving a Void in the White House

docs.abstract: President Trump blamed Democrats and the Mexican government for an increasingly “dangerous” flow of illegal immigrants.
docs.snippet: President Trump blamed Democrats and the Mexican government for an increasingly “dangerous” flow of illegal immigrants.
docs.lead_paragraph: PALM BEACH, Fla. — President Trump, blaming Democrats and the Mexican government for an increasingly “dangerous” flow of illegal immigrants, unleashed a series of fiery tweets on Sunday in which he vowed “NO MORE DACA DEAL” and threatened to walk away from the North American Free Trade Agreement.

headline.main: Venting on Immigration, Trump Vows ‘No More DACA Deal’ and Threatens Nafta
headline.print_headline: As Refugee Caravan Heads North, Trump Rails Against DACA and Nafta
